creator: unknown French|Praxiteles
description: The sculpture known as "Venus d'Arles" was discovered in Arles' Theatre Antique in 1651, in several pieces and lacking arms; it is a Roman copy of a classical Greek work, attributed to Praxiteles. It was restored in 1684 by Girardon. The original sculpture is now at the Louvre (since 1797), after being at Versailles for 112 years. The Musee de l'Arles antique also has a plaster copy of the sculpture in its original state (arms lacking). Another copy is installed in a stairway in the Hotel de Ville, Arles.

creator: unknown Gallo-Roman|unknown French|La Chapelle, Pierre de (Mason)
description: The Arles Amphitheatre (Arenes d'Arles) is a Roman amphitheatre built in 90 AD. It was used as a defensive structure and town shelter after the fall of the Roman Empire, and four towers were added in the 6th century; three remain. The octagonal Gothic style "clocher" or bell tower is all that remains of the Franciscan convent established on this site in 1365; the tower was built by the mason Pierre de la Chapelle in 1469, and restored in 1997. A chapel was built adjoining the bell tower in 1562. In 1883 the Soeurs de Saint Charles purchased the site and established their school there.
